Barrowland	A remote burial ground deep in the Great Forest of the northern continent, one hundred miles north of Oar near the Great Tragic River. Established by the White Rose to seal away the most powerful enemies of the Domination era, it centered on the Great Barrow and a geometric arrangement of lesser burial mounds. Its defenses included the hereditary Eternal Guard, lethal protective spells anchored by fetishes, bound ghosts, an ageless subterranean dragon, and the remnants of an ancient moat; the name also referred more broadly to the nearby Guard compound, inn, and settlement.
Beryl	An ancient maritime city on the northern coast of the southern continent and the oldest of the Jewel Cities, known as their Queen. Governed by rulers called Syndics, it gave its dialect to the Black Company's speech and written Annals. Its long, violent history and landmarks such as the Bastion, Necropolitan Hill, Fortress Island, and the impoverished Groan made it one of the region's most storied cities.
Buskin	The poorest and most downtrodden neighborhood of Juniper, situated low in the valley between two arms of the Wolander Mountains. Its residents endured the city's brutal winters in profound poverty, often scavenging for firewood. The Iron Lily tavern and inn stood within the district, whose dangers and hardships were familiar to few city officials.
Charm|Tower at Charm	The administrative capital and personal palace of the Lady's Empire, in the northern continent. An immense featureless black cube of imported basalt — by far the largest structure in the north — it is surrounded by strewn basalt boulders in every direction save a single perfectly manicured approach, funnelling all land access to a controlled point. Manned by the Lady's functionaries and the Tower Guard, it encloses a smaller inner Tower within one-third of its volume. It serves as the customary east-west demarcation of the Empire, with the Salient and Forsberg to the north and the Jewel City of Opal and the Sea of Torments to the south.
Chimney	A major harbor city sprawling across the slopes of the Salada Peninsula, which projects from the western coast of the northern continent into the Gap. It lies south of Meadenvil, beyond the lesser coastal cities of Tagline, Needle, and Shaker. Poverty was pervasive enough that Croaker believed even broken glass would be gathered for its tiny resale value, while powerful local institutions included the Houses of Istven and the Seamen's Guild.
Cho'n Delor	A haunted ruin above the Second Cataract on the southern continent's great river, its silhouette likened by Willow Swan to a heap of skulls. Two centuries before Croaker's time, the tyrant Paingod ruled it and employed the Black Company against the Triplet Cities in the Pastel Wars. The conflict left all four cities ruined and the surrounding land so haunted that people and animals avoided it.
Duretile	The hereditary castle of Juniper's dukes, occupied by Duke Zimerlan during Shadows Linger. It stood on the highest ridge of the southern arm of the Wolander Mountains, across the Port River valley from the mysterious black castle. Like much of Juniper, the palace had fallen into conspicuous disrepair.
Enclosure	The devotional heart of Juniper, the Enclosure was a walled park of pine groves containing the headquarters of the city's Custodians. Beneath it lay the famous Catacombs, where generations of Juniper's dead were interred, while Duke Zimerlan's palace of Duretile stood high above on the southern ridge of the Wolander Mountains. Though remembered as respectable and park-like in earlier years, it had become threadbare by the time of Shadows Linger.
Forest of Cloud	A massive, dense evergreen forest on the northern continent, situated east of the Salient, west of the major city of Lords, and south of Oar. Its interior included groves of huge, ancient evergreens and offered enough seclusion to conceal camps and travelers. The forest's position made it a significant wilderness between important northern territories of the Lady's Empire.
Forsberg	The northernmost province of the Lady's Empire in the northern continent, Forsberg was its own independent kingdom before the Lady's consolidation wars. The province's capital and largest city is Oar, located in its northernmost reaches; the next most important site is Deal, a major fortress south of Oar. The native language is Forsberger. Forsberg borders the vast Great Forest to the north and the province of the Salient to the south. It became a hotbed of Rebel activity in the war against the Lady's Empire, with the general Raker driving significant Imperial losses there.
Iron Lily	A tavern and inn in Juniper's impoverished Buskin neighborhood, owned by Marron Shed as the third generation of his family to keep it. Shed lived there with his blind, elderly mother June, who helped clean its upstairs rooms. The establishment served poor locals as well as travelers and became an important gathering place in Shadows Linger.
Juniper	A large, independent harbor city-state in the far northwest of the northern continent, built in the Port River valley between two snow-topped arms of the Wolander Mountains. Ruled by Duke Zimerlan from Duretile, it was known for frigid weather and a death-centered religion whose Custodians interred the deceased in immense Catacombs. Notable districts and landmarks included the Buskin, Iron Lily, Enclosure, and the shunned black castle.
Khatovar	A city of Kina cult-worshipers, and the place of origin of the Free Companies of Khatovar—most prominently the Black Company itself—which were created there and sent across the glittering plain into the homeworld and other worlds. Their mission was to find the best location for a sacred religious rite called the Year of the Skulls. Over the centuries that followed, the meaning and nature of Khatovar were entirely lost to later generations of Black Company soldiers. After the Battle of the Barrowland, Croaker vowed to return the Company's Annals to this mysterious origin, setting the course for the Company's long southward odyssey. The name carries translations in different sources: "Khadi's Throne", "Place from which Khadi went forth", or simply "Khadi's gate."
Lords	A major city of the Lady's Empire, east of the Forest of Cloud and west of the Plain of Fear, connected by road to the Salient. Governed by Nightcrawler of the Ten Who Were Taken, it became a focus of Rebel activity and Imperial countermeasures. The Black Company later quartered there during the northern war.
Meadenvil	A major port city and independent principality on the western ocean in the northwestern reaches of the northern continent, south of Juniper and the Wolander Mountains and north of Shaker. An unwalled harbor governed by its own prince, it participated in maritime trade through the Gap and Strait of Vermust toward the Jewel Cities and other ports. Its residents regarded Juniper and that city's zealous cult of the dead as backward, while Croaker found Meadenvil fresh, lively, and refreshing by comparison.
Oar	A large, crowded, walled city in the far north of the Lady's Empire, just south of the Great Forest and north of the fortress at Deal. Once the capital of the independent kingdom of Forsberg, it became the province's capital after the Lady's consolidation wars and remained the last major city in the central northern continent. Oar used the obol as currency, monopolized the Barrowland settlement's fur trade, and contained landmarks ranging from the Black Campus and Mayfield Square to the notorious North Side slum.
Opal	A major harbor city on the southern coast of the northern continent, overlooking the Sea of Torments. A member of the famous Jewel Cities and the only one located outside the southern continent, it is at least two centuries old but younger than Beryl, their ancient queen. Opal serves as a transit hub for sea travelers, speaks the Jewel Cities dialect, and is known for the Gardens, an exclusive establishment serving refined patrons for two hundred years.
Plain of Fear	A bizarre desert in the eastern portion of the northern continent, the Plain of Fear is home to over forty unique and intelligent species found nowhere else: windwhales, flying mantas, reversed centaurs, talking buzzards, and enigmatic talking stones called menhirs, among others. The Plain is also notorious for supernatural "change storms" that can transform any living thing caught in them. At its heart resides Father Tree, an alien entity worshiped by the Plain's creatures and the rare wild human tribes as their god, who serves as its ultimate protector and ruler.
Roses	A major walled city in the central part of the Lady's Empire, enclaved within the Salient province. Despite lying within firmly Imperial territory, Roses holds the unique distinction of being a free republic with its own independent sovereignty. Its walls are painted pale red, three rivers course through it connected by a web of canals, and its numerous arched bridges are among the city's most celebrated features. The Rosean language originated here. A road to the south connects Roses to Meystrikt, the most important fortress of the Salient.
Rust	One of five huge and formidable cities forming an arc east of the Plain of Fear in the northern continent, alongside Frost, Thud, Ade, and Barns. Rust was the focus of numerous protracted and bloody Rebel uprisings against the Lady's Empire. The fighting around Rust was described as particularly bitter and sustained, with both sides driven to extreme measures during prolonged sieges. The city was also notable for its "amazon regiments": Rebel formations composed entirely of women.
Rye	A noteworthy town or city in the northern portion of the Lady's Empire, besieged by the Rebel. Its precise location is not fully given in the Annals, though context places it south of the Salient and west of Lords, in a region associated with Elm, Wist, Jane, and Wine. One of the most effective of the Ten Who Were Taken, Shapeshifter, was dispatched there to hold the city against the Rebel siege.
Salient	A long, arrowhead-shaped province of flatland pointing south between mountain ranges in the northern continent. Its most important city is Roses, a free republican enclave, and its most important fortress is Meystrikt. Forsberg lies to the north, the Forest of Cloud to the east, and a long road links the Salient to the major city of Lords. Presumed one of the earliest provinces absorbed into the Lady's Empire, given its proximity to the Tower at Charm.
Stair of Tear	A mountain range of sandstone bluffs, pillars, and mesas in the northern continent, named after its single steep pass: an old road that climbs steeply through countless switchbacks, resembling from a distance a giant's lopsided stairway. The Windy Country lies immediately to its north, and the Tower at Charm, the capital of the Lady's Empire, lies not far to the south.
Tally	The easternmost province of the Lady's Empire during Shadows Linger, Tally was a formerly independent kingdom described as a bleak land with only two substantial towns. Tome lay two thousand miles east of Charm and served as a garrison town, while Heart was the traditional seat of the Tallylander king. An arc of five massive cities (Rust, Frost, Ade, Barns, and Thud) stood to the west, with the still bleaker kingdom of Tambor to the northeast.
Were	A city or town in the eastern reaches of the Lady's Empire in the northern continent, mentioned once in the Annals by Soulcatcher. Site of a notable battle between Soulcatcher, the most powerful of the Ten Who Were Taken, and Whisper, the most dangerous Rebel leader of the Circle of Eighteen. Soulcatcher cited Were alongside Rust and the Plain of Fear as locations where she had faced Whisper directly.
Windy Country	An inhospitable northern desert west of the Plain of Fear and east of the Forest of Cloud and Lords. Described as a vast emptiness where the wind blows constantly, it has no fixed tracks and was considered worthless by the Lady's Empire. Its deep canyons could provide cover, but travel across its exposed wastes was punishing and dangerous.
Wolander Mountains|Wolanders	A major mountain range in the far northwest of the northern continent. Two snow-topped arms enclose Juniper and the Port River valley, with Duretile on the southern heights and the black castle on the northern. The range extends east of Juniper for at least one hundred miles and reaches the sea to the west.
